<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Borick on 05-28-2002 02:03 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">The number of clerics and the timing on the CH rotation varies from mob to mob.  On most mobs (TOV dragons) my guild uses a four-cleric, four-second rotation. For Avatar of War (The most difficult mob my guild kills at present) we use 10-12 clerics on a two-second rotation.

The actual amount that the clerics heal with each CH varies.  Verant has added a lot of randomness to how mobs do damage, just to limit the effectiveness of CH and rotations.  Flurries, rampages and the ability of a mob to hit in a random pattern within it's attack round all mean that clerics have to worry not about being mana efficient, but in making sure that we always heal within the maximum range of damage the mob can hit for. The irony of these changes is that it only reinforces the reliance of raids on Complete Heal even further.

For example, if Ubermob X 'normally' hits for 1k per second, but can flurry for an additional 4k once every 12 seconds, then every cleric in the rotation must assume an additional 4k of damage on his turn.  This means that many of the heals will be less efficient mana-wise than a Divine Light or Natures Touch would be, but it has to be that way or you couldn't take down these mobs.  On these mobs smaller heals couldn't compensate for the sudden spikes in damage output.

Also note that in order to maintain the longer rotations you're going to need an infastructure for the rotation.  For AOW you will need mages to cast plenty of three-charge mod rods.  Every melee will pick up a mod rod to drop during the fight.  Clerics will use the mod rods to replace mana during the fight, and druids/shamans have the task of keeping the clerics healed.  With practice you can maintain a rotation on any mob almost infinately.  Verant doesn't like it, but that's the only option they give us.  The developers have this unrealistic notion of using mass numbers to kill these mobs rather than 'exploiting' by using strict DPS and cleric rotations, but there's a point of diminishing returns with the 'zerg' method at which the raid lag actually reduces your ability to kill the mob.

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
